This file exists only to materialize /sbin in the shipped ext2 image.

/sbin is one of the kernel's trusted-path granting anchors (cap_policy_lookup
in kernel/cap/cap_policy.c: a binary under /sbin/ may derive policy caps). The
load-bearing invariant (CLAUDE.md 1.2.2) is that the trusted-for-granting tree
MUST equal the write-protected tree: ext2_mount records s_sbin_ino and any
mutation under /sbin then requires CAP_KIND_INSTALL.

If /sbin does not exist in the image, its inode is never recorded, so it is NOT
write-protected — yet cap_policy_lookup still trusts the /sbin/ path prefix. A
DAC-permitted writer could then `mkdir /sbin; cp forged /sbin/login` and forge
authority (e.g. AUTH) by basename, defeating no-ambient-authority. Keeping this
empty file ships /sbin so it is recorded and protected at mount. Same pattern as
/lib/ladybird/.keep. Do not remove without also removing /sbin from the anchor.
